    21 * - all operations that modify content
    22 * - 1. Retrieve data to be applied
    23 * - 2. Extract PKs of to be updated rows
    24 * - 3. Create backup of to be updated rows

    1 /**
    2 * The seeder interface provides the ability to handle all operations, that
    3 * are not DDL specific and thus not a migration.
    4 *
    5 * These operations are currently, but not limited to:
    6 *
    7 * inserting data
    8 * removing data
    9 * searching data
    10 * truncating whole tables
    11 *
    12 * This functionality is provided in two ways to the user. First there are
    13 * traditional seeder. You can call them whenever you want, and how often
    14 * you want. This might be handy when initializing a new development
    15 * environment, but not if you want to use it for the production environment.
    16 *
    17 * The second seeder type, the version controlled seeders, short VC Seeds,
    18 * is targeting the production environment and development environment.
    19 * There is technically no big difference between them, except the following
    20 * details:
    21 *
    22 * A VC Seed can be called from a migration, via seed.execute and seed.link. A
    23 * normal seeder can not. Also A VC Seeder has a down and up function, like
    24 * the way the migrations work, the static has a truncate function instead,
    25 * which gets called before the seed function. This is because a seeder is
    26 * mostly used to initialize something, a VC Seeder instead is used to
    27 * populate changes made to the dataset and to have a clear separation of
    28 * DDL and Data Maniupulations.
    29 * And last but not least, a VC Seed can not be executed if it was already
    30 * executed. You will need to roll back it first, it just acts pretty similar
    31 * to migrations. A normal seed can be executed just as often as you want
    32 * without the need to rollback your data.
    33 *
    34 * To note: If you rollback a migration, linked to a seeder, db-migrate will
    35 * also rollback the seed. This is also a reason why you can't rollback a
    36 * specific migration, you would going to break that much, you probably loose
    37 * a bunch of valueable time.
    38 */
